Nepetalactone (NL) is a major compound sequestered in the glandular trichomes of 

Nepeta
species

(fam. 
Lamiaceae
). In natural sources, this iridoid monoterpene is present in the form of 7S diastereoisomers (

), and their qualitative and quantitative content is species-specific. Many 

Nepeta
species

are well known for their pharmacological properties and are widely used in folk medicine as diuretic, diaphoretic, anti-tussive, anti-spasmodic, anti-asthmatic, febrifuge and sedative agents, against gastrointestinal and respiratory hyperactive disorders (

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

). They also show phytotoxic and allelopathic effects (

, 

; 

), and display behavioural effect on cats (

), and repellent activity (

; 

; 

). Although the biological activities of 

Nepeta
species

have been thoroughly investigated and usually ascribed to nepetalactones, the biosynthesis of these compounds on the molecular level is not entirely understood.

In response to PEG-induced dehydration stress, the closure of stomata on the surface of
N. rtanjensis
( Fig. 1a and b ) and
N. argolica ssp. argolica
leaves ( Fig. 1c and d ) was observed, which was adopted as a strategy to reduce the transpiration and protect the leaves against water loss. Morphology of glandular trichomes of the peltate type , which are considered to be the site of nepetalactone biosynthesis and accumulation (
;
;
;
), was not changed in response to PEG treatment in both
N. rtanjensis
and
N. argolica ssp. argolica
( Fig. 1a–d ).

Four NL stereoisomers with differing stereochemistry at the 4a and 7a positions are observed at different ratios in various
Nepeta species
(
;
;
). The 5,9- DNL, a cyclopentane monoterpenoid of the nepetalactone type with two C ] C bonds is a result of NL oxidation, e.g., dehydrogenation (
;
;
). This compound was identified in the essential oils of a number of
Nepeta species
(
;
;
;
;
,
; Sastry et al., 1972;
). It has also been identified in methanol extracts of several
Nepeta species
, including
N. rtanjensis
and
N. argolica ssp. argolica ( Mišić et al., 2015 )
.
Nepeta rtanjensis
, which is characterized by the presence of trans,cis -NL is a rich source of DNL, while
N. argolica ssp. argolica
accumulates primarily cis,trans -NL and a low amount of DNL. Some of the explanations for this phenomenon could be the higher affinity of the enzyme responsible for the dehydrogenation step towards trans,cis - oriented NL and thus its more efficient conversion into DNL, or the higher stability of cis,trans -NL when compared to trans,cis -NL.

Since the initial discovery in
C. roseus
of CrIS (
), ISs have been functionally characterized in various iridoidproducing species (
